segments.text: Groups that we talked about earlier reacted to this cut off of federal funding as far as projects that they had been relatively assured of getting rehab that had been promised and this type of thing.
How are they reacting?
How do planners react to their different demands that they have coming in now?
Well, the Planning Department of the City of Austin is not involved in the Community Development Program, in the delivery of services directly.
nor are they involved any longer in the planning for the use of those funds.
That's done through the city's human services department.
Federal programs have been centralized in the human services department, while overall comprehensive plans, zoning, and things have been in the planning department.
The neighborhood groups most closely affected by the cutoff of funds, or not cutoff, but the withholding of funds, because the funds are still available, they're just being held.
The withholding of funds has been affected
of groups like Texas Acorn, some of the minority neighborhoods, not well organized, but dependent upon these kind of activities to support the neighborhoods.
They have, they have expressed great concern.
They've repeatedly made statements and tried to work with city officials.
And they're as anxious as we are to resolve it, but we all feel powerless.
It's out of our hands, there's nothing we can do about it.
During the 1950s when the
The federal government had a push for building an interstate highway system of transportation.
What planning was involved by Austin City in order that areas would be best served by the interstate system?
And how were areas impacted in the suburbs in that?
Well, I don't know how planning occurred in Austin.
I suspect the State Highway Department did it all.
This is their headquarters and this is the State Capitol and they're going to take care of it.
I can tell you what the result was.
The result was Interstate 35 came right through the center of the heart of the community.
It segregated the East Austin portion of this community, which was predominantly minority and poor, from the more affluent and business oriented West and Central Austin.
it did in fact sever some 1,500 homes from their historical neighborhood by placing them in the West Austin area when they really had living ties to East Austin.
These homes were greatly dilapidated, problems in it.
1956 the interstate was announced right through
The east side of Austin, accessible to the state capital, the University of Texas, was coming right through the heart of town.
Followed within ten years was the declaration of the Urban Renewal District that removed all the housing from the west side of the freeway, and so the expansion of state government.
It's been viewed, and I think in many respects rightly so, by the East Austinites as a wall and a barrier that
cuts them off from full participation in the community.
And in fact, those that were cut off by it have been removed.
Those who were displaced as a result of interstate highways in the area and as a result of urban renewal programs, how did the planning department in Austin attempt to accommodate their relocating?
Planning departments, to my knowledge, had no role whatsoever.
The Urban Renewal Agency, created in 1956-57, did all of that.
They used the Federal Relocation Act and benefits and all of that, and they did everything.
The city planning department had only one role, and that was in the preparation of the urban renewal plans done by consultants.
The planning department reviewed them, the planning commission reviewed them, and the council adopted them, and that was it.
Obviously there are a great deal of state projects that have impacted the city of Austin.
What are some of the more significant of these within the city?
Where do you start?
Gee, the state has always had the complex from the early day to the layout of the capitol.
From 11th Street to Martin Luther King, 19th Street.
Those were not the original names of the streets.
They were changed several times.
Austin had a very characteristic and something I've seen repeated in other cities.
The rivers of Texas were the north-south streets, and the trees of Texas were the east-west streets.
Those tree names have been replaced with numbers, though in the center city, the rivers still remain.
There's just been a characteristic complete building program based on an old, old plan of the expansion of state government.

Some of the greater impact on the city of Austin has been that when you look at the community in light of its total governmental impact, it's been said that over 50% of the land within the community itself is tax exempt, therefore creating severe economic constraints on city government.
Actions taken by the state and the university, of course, are not subject to approval by the city of Austin.

Street closings have occurred, rerouting of traffic has occurred, significant buildings have been constructed, which may or may not fit into the landscape the community wants to see, but are not under the control of the community.
There's not been any friction that I'm aware of, however.
There's always been a very strong partnership between the state, the city, and the university
And though there are inconveniences, I've never seen outright or been aware of any outright conflict between the two or three.
Which private development projects would you say played a major role in the city's planning history?
Well, I'd have to have some idea of what time frame.
If we look from 1975, from my perspective,
of planning.
Two recent activities have occurred, three now, that I feel will have a long range impact on this community, much longer than perhaps many people are willing to admit.
The city has been in an aggressive downtown redevelopment attitude and the goals have expressed the need for a compact city
Yet in the last three years, three very large, very significant projects have been located just south of Town Lake.
They are going to begin the high impact of existing neighborhoods in that area.
And I foresee a further expansion of the central business district south of Town Lake, something that had never been talked about and really had been discouraged in the goals.
The Hyatt Regency, the American Statesman newspaper,
and now another new hotel will have some very, very long range and serious effects on land values and intrusion in those very close in neighborhoods that exist on that side of the river.
You mentioned earlier dates and a little bit on the methods of review and revision that need to be undertaken for changing the city's comprehensive plan
Has the development of the city's charter itself and the changes in the city charter had a significant role in planning in Austin?
They've had a very significant role in the operation and the role that the city government has played.
They've not had a significant role that I see, in revisions anyway, as far as the impact of planning.
Planning is very strongly recognized and provided for in the charter.
No one has ever attempted to do anything other than strengthen that.
Other revisions have changed the role of the council and the role of other people.
Have ordinances dealing with planning implementation had a significant role in changing planning in Austin?
Yes, particularly in regards to subdivision activity as new development occurs.

New standards based on the master plan for density, for layout, for street facilities, utilities, the development of the CIP itself all critically affect the shape and the level of services this community provides.
How about different controls on height, building height that Austin City has tried to employ?
How has this affected planning?
In the center city, there's been a discussion for some four years about the establishment of height limit zones to protect the view of the capital for those who would be entering this community.
A unanimous proposal for the establishment of a height ceiling in downtown Austin was submitted to the city council over two years ago by the planning commission after long debate.
The council tabled it, and it has never come up again.
and there is still great consternation from the members of the Planning Commission that that is a necessary activity, the Council has not seen fit to pass it.
You mentioned that most of your planning experience with Austin City has been in the recent past.
To the best of your recollection, though, what individuals and what organizational changes within the Austin City Planning Department, as far as administration goes,
have had a significant impact upon planning here.
Let's talk maybe about specific department heads and that.
Well, I think certainly Dick Lilly has had a tremendous impact on what we'll know this city to be in future years.
The commitment made by him and his staff and the Planning Commission and all of those who saw this need to
to involve the citizen in the determination of their own future is something that the city has now embraced and I don't think would ever attempt to change.
The wide concern for citizen participation in this city is so deep-rooted that it's become part of our heritage.
I think Dick Lilly should be given tremendous credit for that as the leader of that and a strong supporter of it.
He also brought, of course, the
the beginning of organization of neighborhood groups, which has led, as I said, to some 65 groups now being recognized by the city.

In my experience, a hearty commitment towards the environment and the protection of the lakes, the protection of the hill country, brought forth the development of the Environmental Resource Management Department, whose sole function it is to look after the environment.

While that's characteristically a planner's role in looking at the development of the city, the sophistication and everything is so great in Austin that this city saw fit to create an entire department whose only role was environmental department, environmental management, and one of the few in the state.
Nationally, that is fairly unique for a city the size of it.
Yes, I believe that's true.
The current director, Dr. Maureen McReynolds, came from San Diego where she was director of environmental
resources.
That was not an uncharacteristic thing in California, but for Texas, we may still be the only city that has that kind of commitment.
They work very, very closely.
Their offices are co-located with the Planning Department, so there's tremendous cooperation.
Have there been significant administrative changes, whether formal or informal, between the Planning Department, the
and the city council and the planning staff and the city manager in Austin?
I'd say yes.
And I'd say that they are formal.
When I first arrived in Austin, the planning department, in accordance with the charter, had full control over all planning activities in the community.
They wrote the capital improvements program.
They provided for federal distribution, federal planning for community development block grants and others.
And over the years since that time, the capital improvements program has become part of the city manager staff and is now reviewed only by the city planning department.
The federal programs have been taken away and planning for those programs has now been placed into another operational department, the human services department.
Issues such as economic development, manpower and jobs, the programs that I operate for rehabilitation and conservation are no longer
an issue for the planning department.
They're not involved in those.
I personally believe they should totally be involved in them, but the current operation is that the planning department does zoning, subdivision, and master plan.
That's it.
All of the implementation, the specifics of where the money goes and when to accomplish what it goes are done in other departments now.
Those functions that are now performed by other departments outside of the planning department,
Have there been administrative changes informally whereby different departments have incorporated plan implementation functions, for example, that are outside of what originally was intended?
Well, the department, the original organization was that the planning department prepared all of the block ramp
plan an application for the development and improvement of the community, and then it was implemented by the city's human services department.
Now the human services department does both the planning and implementation.
The environmental department reviews and has authority over the city's environmental creek and waterways ordinance.
That was never part of the planning department's function, but they played a very strong role in environment up to that point.
though they still do because it all impacts subdivision.

Informally, until the current time, for the past three and a half years, even after planning for federal programs left the planning department, they in fact still were done that way because the human services department came right back and needed help to get the job done.
They didn't have the staff capability to do it.
I think they're getting away from that now.
Is there much of a struggle or competitiveness between different city departments to have more control over plan implementation functions as a result of that?
There is between those two departments.

The feeling in the Human Services Department having control over some five to six million dollars a year, pure plan implementation, neighborhood conservation, neighborhood improvement, neighborhood development, very strong planning roles.
has been that they control that function and they've acted that way.
The planning department has lost any authority to actually get out and implement those kinds of plans.
And it's become a very highly political process.
And many of the projects that are developed now and implemented by the Human Services Department do not reflect adequate planning, nor do they reflect needs of the community.
And they become highly political
projects that are of, at least in my opinion, very nebulous benefit.
You have been associated with Austin City Planning Department formally for the last while.
What would you say the current status of planning is in Austin?
Very active.

the department is moving with the planning commission very very methodically and i think very well organized towards the development of comprehensive new zoning ordinance they're looking at new options for growth management and they're looking for new ways of implementing the issues of the master plan the size of the city the developmental corridor aspects and i'd say they're even they're very very strongly involved in major
developmental issues for the city.

And you would say that perhaps in contrast to other Texas cities where planning is considered an intervention on private property rights, in Austin decisions that are made by planners or let's say by city council or the planning commission are more readily accepted by the public as a result of a greater deal of input then?
Yes, yeah.
I think

The openness and the involvement of citizens still evolves with the complaint of infringement on property rights, but since it's had such a wide dissemination and discussion, which of course takes a long time, which delays your ability to get new plans going, it has characteristically been the strongest stable factor in the community.
There are a variety of different types of influences that can play a role as far as playing in a particular community goes.
What influence would you say that political forces and political aspect has had in planning in Austin?
Well, I think it's been very significant.
In 1976 when Jeff Frieden was elected mayor,

along with the council, who was deemed to be a liberal group of individuals, there was a very strong commitment toward limited growth, managed growth, not to be construed as no growth, but a management of our environmental resources, a sensible development of our community in a way that was beneficial to everyone who was here, and not to create another Houston or Dallas or whatever, not being derogatory towards them.
That council came in with a very strong mandate to control, to keep Austin, Austin.
To an extent it was successful, to another extent it was not, and I think Jeff Friedman would be the first to say so.
Do you have to know offhand approximately what percentage population increased Austin experienced from 70 to 80?
Yes, in 1970 the population was 250,000.
In 1980, it was 354,000, roughly one-third.
Historically, that is a larger increase than would be expected in population.
Sure, sure.
Austin has been a very rapid growth.
Now between 76 and 78 during the Freedmen Council, growth occurred, but it was not as rapid as it has been the last two years.
nor as rapid as it was from 70 to 75.
Would you say that religion has been a significant influence as regards planning in Austin?
No, I don't think so.

I would say that the churches are organized and do exercise political power in the community, but I've not seen any activities that would attempt to manipulate or influence the general planning community.
How have the various ethnic groups within Austin impacted planning here?
Very much.
Very much.
Particularly the Mexican-American community.
The growth of that community has been very strong.
It is an increasing percentage of the overall population.
You would estimate approximately what percent?
Twenty-seven percent of the community.
And I think that we can say that that is growing.

Since the early 1970s, particularly as you saw the 1976 council, the Jeff Friedman council, pay more and greater attention to the issues of the poor, the minorities, the impact on the eastern side of the community.
I think there's been a greater organization, greater impact, and now, of course, much greater investment
in fixing up those parts of the community.
So right now they're a very formidable force in the community.
Do ethnic groups primarily reside in lower income areas in Austin?
Can it be typified in that sense, or is that too broad a generalization?
Well, the poor areas of the city are predominantly minority occupied.
That doesn't mean that there aren't affluent
Minority workers live in other parts.
But if you look at the concentration of minorities in this community on a map, you are also looking at the poor areas of the community.
And that is unusual for any town.
No, it's typical of every country in the world.
How has their involvement in the planning process, let's say through the neighborhood groups organization, been?
Has it been active?
Has it been solicited as far as changes, let's say from major thoroughfares or public projects?

There have been solicitations, but they have been characteristically less organized and have less of a vocal, they have vocal people, a cadre of small groups who are very vocal in the community and pushing the interest.
They have not been able to have the hundreds of people that typically come out of Anglo areas.
If you have a neighborhood issue, every homeowner in the area is interested and you can make it.
make a statement, and have everyone in your neighborhood there.
You can't do that in the minority areas of the city.
You have the spokesmen, and by and large, 85%, 95% of the people won't participate.
They will sympathize, but they won't get involved.
But as a result of their activities, more and more investment, both general tax funds through its city's general obligation bonds, and almost exclusively the federal program.
have all been chartered towards the improvement of those areas and the improvement of living conditions in them.
Have activities of the black community in Austin significantly impacted planning, or do they constitute a significant percentage that they would have that kind of influence?
The black community in Austin has been decreasing.
And it's, I don't know if it's philosophical or not, but we've looked at the history
of South Texas cities.

As we move north, we're the most northern city, I believe, I can't speak about Houston, but coming out of the valley from the Mexican border, we are probably the most northern city with a large, organized Mexican-American community within it.
And that community is growing.
looking at South Texas, San Antonio, those areas, it has happened that as the Mexican-American community increased, the black community and in some respects even the Anglo community has decreased.
We don't see in Austin a decrease in the Anglo community, but we do see a continual erosion of the percentage of the total population that the black population is.
As far as participation as a result of employment in the planning department or as a result of being elected to office, have ethnic groups played a significant role in the planning?
Yes, they have.
There is both factors.
Representation on the city council and on commissions by both black and Mexican-American individuals have
have focused the needs and funds for that matter on East Austin and South Austin, where the minorities predominantly live.
Employment within the city under the city's affirmative action plan has been significant, and minorities are well represented in many, many areas of the city.
Not to the level that the plan would require them to be, but significant nonetheless.
Has this been
a recent factor, or has this always existed historically in Austin, that degree of visibility by ethnic groups?
I'd say it's not more than eight or nine years old.
Fairly recent.
Yes.
As an example, the 1924 plan, I believe, provided for a separate but equal community, and it provided for the segregation of black people
in East Austin specifically.
And of course during those times segregation was the law of the land, but yet here was a public document adopted.
No one of course today supports that, but it was public policy during those times that separate but equal was in fact going to occur in Austin.
Lawsuits and of course everything occurred to that, and East Austin is exactly that case.
As a result of that policy and a result of that program
we have a predominantly minority area of the city which is run down and needs significant investment to bring it back.
You mentioned back in 1839 when the state legislature was looking for a city in which to base a capital for taxes.
Austin was considered one of the advantages it had over other areas as far as being created as a new city was its central location.
What other geographic factors
have influenced planning in Austin?
The Highland Lakes and the Colorado River have been an extremely important factor.
It's provided a virtually unlimited water supply to this community.
The hills themselves, the Edwards Plateau and the Central Texas Hills, the heritage of all of Texas, begins in Austin.
The hill country
has been the premier residential area of this community.
It is the thing to which everyone aspires to live in, and it is the area that is most sensitive environmentally.
And so you have the conflict of everyone wants to live in the central Texas hills, yet at the same time, it's the area that can least support that urbanization.
That's been a very strong characteristic of the community, trying to determine how much can we afford to allow development to occur in those hills.
Realizing that type of desirability, how has planning in Austin attempted to alleviate that kind of conflict?

Well, planning in Austin has attempted, by virtue of its environmental basis, to establish growth corridors in the city that will channel public investment and private development into areas of less sensitive environmental characteristics.

What that has meant is that the city has adopted a growth corridor concept that says the Austin ought to grow north and south and stay out of the hill country, utilize it as a resource for this community, but limit densities, limit public investment so that we do not encourage rapid urbanization of the area, which supports our water supply and all of the other factors.
That's been effective, at least the capital improvements program.
Subdivision activity and all has been
very strongly related to protecting the Hill Country.
What sociological influences would you say have affected planning in Austin?
The high level of education as a result of state employment and the University of Texas have brought a very sophisticated and very
knowledgeable population to Austin.
Especially for a city its size.
Especially for a city its size.
As the state capital and the seat of its largest university, the city has benefited because of the tremendous pool of knowledge and sophistication that's here.
Therefore, the planning activities of this community have been much deeper thought and widely discussed through the university, through the state, through all of the
thousands and thousands of people who have tremendous academic credentials in various, various forms.
The city has benefited tremendously from that.
They've had the university's resources, the state's resources assisting in the development of the future of this community.
Geologically, environmentally, organizationally, no area in the city has been untouched by that talent pool.
You mentioned earlier that the military has not played a particularly important role in planning in Austin, military projects and that.
So we can discount that as a major influence on planning here.

Except as most recent, there is a current problem involved with the location of the existing airport and the conflict in the air traffic that's occurring between our city airport and the Bergstrom Air Force Base.
That has come over the past two years to result in studies that say the city must build a new airport.
And one of the options at that time was to suggest a co-location of the city and the military utilizing Bergstrom as a
